    <p>I bought two of these suc­cu­lents when there were four to five flo­rets a pot. They have grown so won­der­fully. What are these plants and how do I prop­a­gate them?</p>
    <p>Laura Hwang</p>
    <p>The plant is com­monly called the Chi­nese Worm­wood (botan­i­cal name: Crossostep­hium chi­nense) and is a shrub with highly or­na­men­tal, sil­ver leaves. It can be prop­a­gated via stem-cut­tings.</p>
    <p>The Chi­nese Worm­wood can be dif­fi­cult to cul­ti­vate in Sin­ga­pore as it re­quires well-drained soil that dries out slightly be­tween each wa­ter­ing. It should also be pro­tected from the rain with a shel­ter over it for the best re­sults. The plant is best grown un­der direct sun­light for at least six hours daily.</p>

